{"id": "CONTROL-licensing-page-never-says-commercial-use-free", "kind": "doc-contains", "must_fail": true, "file": "specs/macos-ci/04-tart-licensing-risk.md", "site": "tart", "page": "/licensing/", "expect": "commercial use free up to 100 CPU cores", "claim": "CONTROL: 04 previously put this sentence IN QUOTATION MARKS and attributed it to tart.run/licensing/. The page has never contained it -- the string is lifted verbatim from the master brief's G4. Its evidence must NOT verify. If it ever starts passing, upstream adopted the wording and this control retires. The page's real sentence is pinned by tart-free-tier-100-cores-4-workers. Paired with tart-licensing-page-exists, which proves the page resolves, so this failure means 'the sentence is absent', not 'the page is gone'.", "polarity": "negative"}
{"id": "CONTROL-tart-blog-is-outside-doc-index-domain", "kind": "doc-index", "must_fail": true, "file": "specs/macos-ci/04-tart-licensing-risk.md", "site": "tart", "expect": "/blog/2025/10/27/press-release-cirrus-labs-successfully-enforces-its-fair-source-license/", "claim": "CONTROL / SECOND CARVE-OUT (OQ-08). This page returns HTTP 200 and is 04 \u00a73's entire enforcement precedent, yet it is ABSENT from the tart search index -- which holds 20 doc pages and zero blog posts. Its evidence must NOT verify. This is G19's failure mode on tart.run: an agent that 'defaults to refuted' on a doc-index miss would delete a real, load-bearing citation. NEVER refute a tart.run/blog/** URL by querying the index; curl it. If this ever starts PASSING, MkDocs began indexing blog posts and the carve-out can retire. Positive control: tart-licensing-page-exists.", "polarity": "negative"}
{"id": "tart-2025-enforcement-press-release-is-live", "kind": "http-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/04-tart-licensing-risk.md", "expect": "This was an exceptional case", "claim": "The Oct-2025 enforcement post EXISTS and SAYS what 04 \u00a73 quotes: the CEO calls it 'an exceptional case'. Reaches the live page via curl because doc-contains cannot (OQ-08). CAVEAT: cli-help greps stdout+stderr and ignores curl's exit code, so a network outage FAILS this claim rather than reporting UNREACHABLE:. [OQ-26] Upgraded from `cli-help curl -fsSL` to the native `http-contains` kind. It proves the page SAYS this, which g4-enforcement-press-release-returns-200 (http-status) deliberately does not: existence and content are different propositions and now have different claims. A non-2xx yields STRUCTURE:, never a verdict on the sentence.", "url": "https://tart.run/blog/2025/10/27/press-release-cirrus-labs-successfully-enforces-its-fair-source-license/"}
{"id": "tart-2025-enforcement-names-competing-product", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/04-tart-licensing-risk.md", "argv": ["curl", "-fsSL", "https://tart.run/blog/2025/10/27/press-release-cirrus-labs-successfully-enforces-its-fair-source-license/"], "expect": "competing product", "claim": "The distinguishing fact in the enforced case was building a COMPETING PRODUCT, not mere core-count overage. Backs 04 \u00a73's central qualification. Same curl caveat as tart-2025-enforcement-press-release-is-live."}
{"id": "tart-2023-post-defines-server-installation", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/04-tart-licensing-risk.md", "argv": ["curl", "-fsSL", "https://tart.run/blog/2023/02/11/changing-tart-license/"], "expect": "without a physical display connected", "claim": "The 2023 post defines 'server installation' as Tart on a physical device with no physical display connected. This is the sentence 04 \u00a71 paraphrases; the paraphrase is now marked as one. EXPECT DELIBERATELY SHORTENED: the fuller literal 'on a physical device without a physical display connected' spans a NEWLINE in the page source, and cli-help's check_contains is a bare `in` with NO whitespace normalization (unlike doc-contains' norm_text). Same curl caveat."}
{"id": "tart-2023-post-hdmi-dummy-plug-example", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/04-tart-licensing-risk.md", "argv": ["curl", "-fsSL", "https://tart.run/blog/2023/02/11/changing-tart-license/"], "expect": "HDMI Dummy Plug", "claim": "The 2023 post's worked example: a Mac Mini with an HDMI Dummy Plug is a SERVER; a Mac Mini on a desk with a display is a PERSONAL COMPUTER. This is why a headless CI Mac counts toward the 100-core ceiling (04 \u00a71, \u00a74). Same curl caveat."}
{"id": "tart-2023-post-royalty-free-not-agpl", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/04-tart-licensing-risk.md", "argv": ["curl", "-fsSL", "https://tart.run/blog/2023/02/11/changing-tart-license/"], "expect": "royalty-free and does not have the viral properties of AGPL", "claim": "Personal-computer usage is royalty-free and non-viral. NOTE the full upstream sentence is 'Usage on personal computers AND BEFORE REACHING THE 100 CPU CORES LIMIT is royalty-free...' -- 04 originally elided the middle clause behind an ellipsis. Same curl caveat."}
