{"id": "utm-apple-backend-no-multiple-displays", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/06-utm-macos-guest.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/advanced/multiple-displays/", "expect": "macOS Apple backend (macOS guests) does not support multiple graphical displays", "claim": "G6 upheld, verbatim: the Apple backend does not support multiple graphical displays for a macOS guest. Any multi-head design for the UTM lane is a non-starter."}
{"id": "utm-rosetta-is-for-linux-guests-only", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/06-utm-macos-guest.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/advanced/rosetta/", "expect": "Rosetta allows you to run Intel Linux executables in an Apple Silicon Linux virtual machine", "claim": "G7 upheld: advanced/rosetta scopes Rosetta to x86_64 binaries inside a LINUX guest, never a macOS guest. The Rosetta toggle's presence on settings-apple/virtualization means the Apple backend exposes the toggle, not that a macOS guest can use it. NOTE: a naive `curl | grep 'macOS guest'` against this page returns a MATCH -- from the nav sidebar's `... Preferences | macOS | Guest Support ...`, not from the prose. That is why this claim is doc-contains (page body via the index) and not a raw fetch. See OQ-12."}
{"id": "utm-apple-serial-is-ptty-only", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/06-utm-macos-guest.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/scripting/reference/", "expect": "only PTTY is supported", "claim": "the `apple serial configuration` record's `interface` enum lists ptty/tcp/unavailable but the doc's own parenthetical restricts the Apple backend to PTTY. This is why 06 s6 tells you to `screen /dev/ttysNNN` and why `utmctl attach` (host end of a ptty) is the only guest-facing channel utmctl offers a macOS guest."}
{"id": "utm-trackpad-requires-ventura-guest", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/06-utm-macos-guest.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/settings-apple/virtualization/", "expect": "Requires Ventura or higher guest", "claim": "the Apple-backend Trackpad toggle is gated on a macOS 13+ (Ventura) GUEST. This sentence lives on the page G10 never found, at the URL G10 replaced with a fabricated one. Its doc-index twin is utm-virtualization-page-exists."}
{"id": "utm-apple-backend-is-only-way-to-run-macos", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/settings-apple/settings-apple/", "expect": "It is the only way to run macOS virtualized on Apple Silicon", "claim": "UTM's own positioning of the Apple backend, quoted in 06 s9a and 07's index row. Together with utm-apple-backend-less-mature-than-qemu it is the doc-sourced basis for the House Stance that UTM is the interactive escape hatch."}
{"id": "utm-apple-backend-less-mature-than-qemu", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/settings-apple/settings-apple/", "expect": "supports only virtualization and is less mature than QEMU", "claim": "UTM says the Apple backend is less mature than QEMU. Paired with utm-apple-backend-is-only-way-to-run-macos: a macOS guest has no choice of backend, so it inherits every Apple-backend gap in 06 s2."}
{"id": "utm-no-tso-toggle-on-apple-virtualization", "kind": "doc-contains", "must_fail": true, "file": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/settings-apple/virtualization/", "expect": "TSO", "claim": "NEGATIVE PROBE: the Apple-backend virtualization settings page never mentions TSO, though settings-qemu/qemu asserts an Apple-backend equivalent exists (utm-tso-apple-equivalent-is-asserted). This proves the PAGE is silent; it does NOT prove no toggle exists -- that step is inference from absence, so 07:25 keeps its <!-- UNVERIFIED --> marker and cites OQ-10. Paired with CONTROL-utm-apple-virtualization-page-has-toggles; without that control an empty page would satisfy this probe. [GB5] The pairing named in this prose is now ENFORCED by tools/verify_claims.py: a must_fail doc-contains probe must carry a `control`. Previously the pairing was stated here and enforced nowhere -- break or delete the control and the gate stayed green at 243/243 while this probe silently went vacuous, because a page with EMPTY indexed text satisfies 'the page does not say TSO'. Closes OQ-19.", "control": "CONTROL-utm-apple-virtualization-page-has-toggles", "polarity": "negative"}
{"id": "CONTROL-utm-apple-virtualization-page-has-toggles", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/settings-apple/virtualization/", "expect": "Balloon Device", "claim": "CONTROL for utm-no-tso-toggle-on-apple-virtualization: this page DOES enumerate Apple-backend toggles. If this fails, 'TSO was absent' proves nothing -- the page would have been empty or gone."}
{"id": "utm-tso-apple-equivalent-is-asserted", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/settings-qemu/qemu/", "expect": "not supported on macOS however when using the Apple virtualization backend, a similar option is available", "claim": "verbatim, inside the `Use TSO` bullet (confirmed by pulling 900 chars of surrounding context: the sentence follows the TSO paragraph and precedes `Use local time for base clock`). UTM asserts an Apple-backend TSO equivalent EXISTS and never names it. No page in the 78-page index documents it. See OQ-10."}
{"id": "utm-settings-qemu-devices-page-exists", "kind": "doc-index", "file": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "site": "utm", "expect": "/settings-qemu/devices/devices/", "claim": "G10 listed this URL as 404 and forbade fetching it. It is in the index and returns HTTP 200. One of the three URLs pruned on a false premise."}
{"id": "utm-settings-qemu-drive-page-exists", "kind": "doc-index", "file": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "site": "utm", "expect": "/settings-qemu/drive/drive/", "claim": "G10 listed this URL as 404 and forbade fetching it. It is in the index and returns HTTP 200."}
{"id": "utm-guest-support-sharing-page-exists", "kind": "doc-index", "file": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "site": "utm", "expect": "/guest-support/sharing/sharing/", "claim": "G10 listed this URL as 404 and forbade fetching it. It is in the index and returns HTTP 200."}
{"id": "utm-real-devices-page-exists", "kind": "doc-index", "file": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "site": "utm", "expect": "/settings-apple/devices/devices/", "claim": "the POSITIVE TWIN of CONTROL-utm-settings-apple-devices-is-fabricated. The real Apple Devices page is /settings-apple/devices/devices/ (200); the fabricated one G10 cited was /settings-apple/devices/ (404, absent from the index). Both claims must hold, or the doc-index oracle is not discriminating between them."}
{"id": "utm-apple-devices-serial-child-exists", "kind": "doc-index", "file": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "site": "utm", "expect": "/settings-apple/devices/serial/", "claim": "07:18 describes the Devices page as a TOC over Display/Network/Serial. That description comes from the NAV, not the page body -- the body only says how to add/remove a device. This claim substantiates the TOC's contents from the index's own page list instead. CAUTION: UTM's rendered Apple nav ALSO shows a `Port Forwarding` entry, but its href points at /settings-qemu/devices/network/port-forwarding/ and both Apple-side candidate URLs 404. The nav is not a page list; the index is."}
{"id": "utm-virtiofs-mount-command", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/06-utm-macos-guest.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/guest-support/macos/", "expect": "mount_virtiofs", "claim": "the macOS-guest VirtioFS share is mounted with `mount_virtiofs share <mount point>`, documented ONLY as a manual per-boot command. No fstab/launchd equivalent is documented for a macOS guest (contrast advanced/rosetta, which gives an /etc/fstab line for a LINUX guest). 06:76 keeps its marker; see OQ-11."}
{"id": "utm-clipboard-uses-spice-vdagent-not-guest-agent", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/06-utm-macos-guest.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/guest-support/macos/", "expect": "spice-vdagent", "claim": "macOS-guest clipboard sharing installs spice-vdagent/spice-vdagentd via `Install Guest Tools`. This is NOT the QEMU guest agent of 05 s2.2 and does not unlock guest-exec or file I/O. Do not conflate the two `guest tools`; the conflation would falsely reopen the utmctl exec/file/ip-address path refuted by utmctl-exec-needs-qemu-guest-agent."}
{"id": "utm-recovery-mode-disables-sip", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/06-utm-macos-guest.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/advanced/recovery/", "expect": "System Integrity Protection", "claim": "recovery mode (1TR, macOS 13+, Apple-backend only) is what `utmctl start --recovery` reaches, and its documented purpose includes disabling SIP. Unlike --disposable and usb, --recovery is a start flag that genuinely works for a macOS guest -- the counterexample that keeps 05 s4.3's `--help` lesson from becoming `no start flag works`."}
{"id": "utm-apple-drive-has-sparse-image-format", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/07-utm-settings-appendix.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/settings-apple/drive/", "expect": "macOS 26+ Use Apple Sparse Image Format", "claim": "UTM's Apple-backend drive settings expose an `Apple Sparse Image Format` option gated on macOS 26+. Independent corroboration, from a second vendor, that the sparse/ASIF format is a real macOS 26+ disk format -- the same format tart calls `disk_format = \"asif\"` in OQ-01. Does not settle whether it preserves unlink residue."}
{"id": "utmctl-file-help-admits-guest-agent", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "file", "--help"], "expect": "Guest agent file operations", "claim": "utmctl's own help text calls `file` a GUEST AGENT operation -- the clearest self-admission of the 05 s2.2 gate. Unlike utmctl-help-lists-exec this probe is not merely `the verb parses`: the parser itself names the missing dependency. The refutation of any hope that it works on a macOS guest is utmctl-exec-needs-qemu-guest-agent."}
{"id": "utmctl-usb-help-lists-connect", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "usb", "--help"], "expect": "connect", "claim": "TRAP, twin of utmctl-start-help-lists-disposable: `utmctl usb` advertises list/connect/disconnect on every host, including one that can only run Apple-backend macOS guests. A subcommand in --help proves it parses, not that it works. The refutation is utmctl-usb-is-qemu-only."}
{"id": "utmctl-start-help-lists-recovery", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "start", "--help"], "expect": "--recovery", "claim": "`utmctl start --recovery` parses. Unlike its sibling --disposable, this flag DOES work for an Apple-backend macOS guest (macOS 13+): see utm-recovery-mode-disables-sip. The pair is the point -- --help cannot tell you which of two adjacent flags is real."}
{"id": "utmctl-delete-help-says-no-confirmation", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "delete", "--help"], "expect": "there is no confirmation", "claim": "utmctl delete's own help text states there is no confirmation, corroborating 05 s2.1's `No confirmation dialog -- irreversible` for the AppleScript `delete` verb it wraps."}
{"id": "utmctl-attach-help-has-index", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "attach", "--help"], "expect": "--index", "claim": "`utmctl attach [--index N]` selects among serial devices. attach reads the HOST end of a ptty and needs no guest agent, which is why 05 s4.2's working set is `lifecycle plus host-side serial` rather than lifecycle-only."}
{"id": "utmctl-usb-group-has-no-debug-flag", "kind": "cli-help", "must_fail": true, "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "usb", "--help"], "expect": "--debug", "claim": "NEGATIVE PROBE refuting 05:263's `Every subcommand accepts the global --debug and --hide`. The container commands `usb` and `file` accept only -h; --debug/--hide live on the LEAF subcommands (`utmctl usb list --help` does show them). Paired with CONTROL-utmctl-usb-help-prints-subcommands: without it, `--debug absent` would be equally satisfied by utmctl printing nothing at all.", "control": "CONTROL-utmctl-usb-help-prints-subcommands", "polarity": "negative"}
{"id": "CONTROL-utmctl-usb-help-prints-subcommands", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "usb", "--help"], "expect": "SUBCOMMANDS", "claim": "CONTROL for utmctl-usb-group-has-no-debug-flag: the SAME argv DOES emit help text. If this fails, `--debug was absent` proves nothing -- the command errored or printed nothing."}
{"id": "utmctl-usb-leaf-does-have-debug-flag", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "usb", "list", "--help"], "expect": "--debug", "claim": "the positive half of the 05:263 correction: --debug/--hide DO exist on the leaf subcommand `utmctl usb list`. Read with utmctl-usb-group-has-no-debug-flag, this pins the real rule -- every LEAF subcommand takes the globals; the two group commands do not."}
{"id": "utm-app-version-is-4-7-5", "kind": "file-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "target": "/Applications/UTM.app/Contents/Info.plist", "expect": "<string>4.7.5</string>", "claim": "UTM.app on this host is 4.7.5, the version 05 s4.1 reports from `utmctl version`. Read from the bundle's XML Info.plist, which costs nothing and mutates nothing -- whereas `utmctl version` dispatches an Apple Event and LAUNCHES UTM.app if it is not running. Same fact, no side effect. Host-specific by design: when UTM updates, this claim fails and 05 must be re-read."}
{"id": "xaudit-08-tart-clone-syntax", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/08-dotfiles-test-harness.md", "argv": ["tart", "clone", "--help"], "expect": "tart clone <source-name> <new-name>", "claim": "08's `tart clone <golden-image> <ephemeral-name>` is correct, verified against the installed CLI's own USAGE line. RETIRES the marker at 08:72, which said `cross-check against 01-tart-core.md` -- a sibling spec is not a source; the binary is."}
{"id": "xaudit-08-tart-run-no-graphics", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/08-dotfiles-test-harness.md", "argv": ["tart", "run", "--help"], "expect": "Don't open a UI window.", "claim": "08's `tart run <clone-name> --no-graphics` is correct: the flag exists and its help text is `Don't open a UI window.` RETIRES the marker at 08:107. Note this proves the flag PARSES; that headless boot then succeeds on a macOS 15+ host still depends on G8's keychain requirement."}
{"id": "xaudit-08-tart-dir-is-not-a-global-flag", "kind": "cli-help", "must_fail": true, "file": "specs/macos-ci/08-dotfiles-test-harness.md", "argv": ["tart", "--help"], "expect": "--dir", "claim": "NEGATIVE PROBE refuting 08's `tart --dir` (used at :74 and :110). --dir is NOT a tart global option; it belongs to `tart run`. The correct form is `tart run <vm> --dir=<[name:]path[:options]>`. Paired with CONTROL-xaudit-08-tart-help-prints-globals -- without it, `--dir absent` would be equally satisfied by tart printing nothing.", "control": "CONTROL-xaudit-08-tart-help-prints-globals", "polarity": "negative"}
{"id": "CONTROL-xaudit-08-tart-help-prints-globals", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/08-dotfiles-test-harness.md", "argv": ["tart", "--help"], "expect": "--version", "claim": "CONTROL for xaudit-08-tart-dir-is-not-a-global-flag: the SAME argv DOES print its global options (--version is one). If this fails, `--dir was absent` proves nothing -- tart printed nothing."}
{"id": "xaudit-08-tart-dir-automounts-to-shared-files", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/08-dotfiles-test-harness.md", "argv": ["tart", "run", "--help"], "expect": "/Volumes/My Shared Files", "claim": "`tart run --dir` uses the com.apple.virtio-fs.automount tag by default, which auto-mounts the share at /Volumes/My Shared Files inside a macOS guest. 08 says the dotfiles source is `mounted via tart --dir` but never names the guest-side path the harness must read from. Corroborated by xaudit-08-tart-dir-automount-documented."}
{"id": "xaudit-08-tart-dir-requires-ventura-guest", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/08-dotfiles-test-harness.md", "argv": ["tart", "run", "--help"], "expect": "macOS guests must be", "claim": "`tart run --dir` requires the HOST to be macOS 13.0+ and the macOS GUEST to be macOS 13.0+ as well. 08's harness plan mounts the dotfiles tree this way, so it silently drops support for a macOS 12 guest. Exactly the same Ventura gate UTM's VirtioFS carries (06 s3.1) -- both are Virtualization.framework, not a tart or UTM feature."}
{"id": "xaudit-08-tart-dir-automount-documented", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/08-dotfiles-test-harness.md", "site": "tart", "page": "/quick-start/", "expect": "All shared directories are automatically mounted to", "claim": "tart's own quick-start confirms the auto-mount behaviour for macOS guests, independent of the --help text. doc-contains partner for xaudit-08-tart-dir-automounts-to-shared-files."}
{"id": "xaudit-08-tart-exec-requires-guest-agent", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/08-dotfiles-test-harness.md", "argv": ["tart", "exec", "--help"], "expect": "Requires Tart Guest Agent running in a guest VM", "claim": "`tart exec` needs the Tart Guest Agent (its help adds: all non-vanilla Cirrus Labs images already have it). So the tart-vs-UTM asymmetry is NOT `tart has exec, UTM does not` -- BOTH exec paths are agent-gated. The real asymmetry: tart's agent is prebuilt into the images, and `tart ip`'s DEFAULT dhcp resolver needs no agent at all, whereas utmctl's ip-address has only the agent path (utmctl-exec-needs-qemu-guest-agent). 08 is right to use ssh, but for this reason, not the one it gives."}

