{"id": "no-xcode-select-in-zsh-dotfiles-tracked", "kind": "cli-help", "must_fail": true, "file": "specs/macos-ci/09-dotfiles-under-test.md", "argv": ["git", "-C", "/Users/bossjones/dev/bossjones/zsh-dotfiles", "grep", "-h", "-o", "xcode-select"], "expect": "xcode-select", "claim": "G12: `xcode-select` appears in NO tracked file of zsh-dotfiles, so the golden image must own Xcode CLT. RETIRED the former `expect: \":\"`, which git's own `fatal:` diagnostic satisfies. `grep -h -o` echoes the matched text itself, so a match is proved by a token no error path can emit. Paired with CONTROL-git-grep-o-emits-matched-text. INVARIANT (b), SECOND CLAUSE: when a true negative implies NO OUTPUT, a same-argv positive control is a logical impossibility -- the same command can never print anything when the claim holds. The control must therefore run the same command SHAPE against the same substrate with a pattern KNOWN to match, and must assert a literal that the command's ERROR paths cannot produce. A bare ':' fails this: `fatal: cannot change to '<path>': No such file or directory` contains one, so a ':'-keyed control PASSES against a repo that does not exist.", "control": "CONTROL-git-grep-o-emits-matched-text", "polarity": "negative"}
{"id": "CONTROL-git-grep-o-emits-matched-text", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/09-dotfiles-under-test.md", "argv": ["git", "-C", "/Users/bossjones/dev/bossjones/zsh-dotfiles", "grep", "-h", "-o", "stdinIsATTY"], "expect": "stdinIsATTY", "claim": "POSITIVE CONTROL for no-xcode-select-in-zsh-dotfiles-tracked. Same command SHAPE, same substrate, a pattern KNOWN to match. Supersedes CONTROL-git-grep-c-emits-colon-when-present, which expected only ':' and therefore PASSED against /nonexistent-repo -- proven, not argued. If the repo path ever breaks, this control fails loudly and 'xcode-select was absent' stops meaning anything. INVARIANT (b), SECOND CLAUSE: when a true negative implies NO OUTPUT, a same-argv positive control is a logical impossibility -- the same command can never print anything when the claim holds. The control must therefore run the same command SHAPE against the same substrate with a pattern KNOWN to match, and must assert a literal that the command's ERROR paths cannot produce. A bare ':' fails this: `fatal: cannot change to '<path>': No such file or directory` contains one, so a ':'-keyed control PASSES against a repo that does not exist."}
{"id": "no-ansible-in-zsh-dotfiles-tracked", "kind": "cli-help", "must_fail": true, "file": "specs/macos-ci/09-dotfiles-under-test.md", "argv": ["git", "-C", "/Users/bossjones/dev/bossjones/zsh-dotfiles", "grep", "-h", "-o", "-i", "ansible"], "expect": "nsible", "claim": "G9, half of it: zsh-dotfiles has no Ansible in any tracked file. The OTHER repo does -- see ansible-in-prep-brewfile-line-57. RETIRED the former `expect: \":\"`. `-o` echoes the matched text, so `nsible` covers `ansible` and `Ansible`; the all-caps spelling is covered separately by no-ansible-uppercase-in-zsh-dotfiles-tracked, because `-o` preserves case and no single lowercase literal can match every casing. Paired with CONTROL-git-grep-o-i-emits-matched-text. INVARIANT (b), SECOND CLAUSE: when a true negative implies NO OUTPUT, a same-argv positive control is a logical impossibility -- the same command can never print anything when the claim holds. The control must therefore run the same command SHAPE against the same substrate with a pattern KNOWN to match, and must assert a literal that the command's ERROR paths cannot produce. A bare ':' fails this: `fatal: cannot change to '<path>': No such file or directory` contains one, so a ':'-keyed control PASSES against a repo that does not exist.", "control": "CONTROL-git-grep-o-i-emits-matched-text", "polarity": "negative"}
