{"id": "prep-repo-has-no-ansible-playbook", "kind": "cli-help", "must_fail": true, "file": "specs/macos-ci/09-dotfiles-under-test.md", "argv": ["git", "-C", "/Users/bossjones/dev/bossjones/zsh-dotfiles-prep", "grep", "-h", "-o", "-i", "-e", "hosts:", "--", "*.yml", "*.yaml"], "expect": "osts:", "claim": "G9's defensible core: zsh-dotfiles-prep contains no Ansible playbook -- no `hosts:` key in any tracked YAML -- so ansible is an installed tool, not the harness. The companion prep-repo-has-no-become-key covers `become:`; one `expect` cannot cover two alternated patterns under `-o`. RETIRED the former `expect: \":\"`. Paired with CONTROL-prep-grep-o-i-emits-matched-text, which proves the *.yml/*.yaml pathspec genuinely matches tracked files in THIS repo. INVARIANT (b), SECOND CLAUSE: when a true negative implies NO OUTPUT, a same-argv positive control is a logical impossibility -- the same command can never print anything when the claim holds. The control must therefore run the same command SHAPE against the same substrate with a pattern KNOWN to match, and must assert a literal that the command's ERROR paths cannot produce. A bare ':' fails this: `fatal: cannot change to '<path>': No such file or directory` contains one, so a ':'-keyed control PASSES against a repo that does not exist.", "control": "CONTROL-prep-grep-o-i-emits-matched-text", "polarity": "negative"}
{"id": "CONTROL-prep-grep-o-i-emits-matched-text", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/09-dotfiles-under-test.md", "argv": ["git", "-C", "/Users/bossjones/dev/bossjones/zsh-dotfiles-prep", "grep", "-h", "-o", "-i", "-e", "name:", "--", "*.yml", "*.yaml"], "expect": "ame:", "claim": "POSITIVE CONTROL for prep-repo-has-no-ansible-playbook and prep-repo-has-no-become-key. Same command SHAPE, same substrate, same *.yml/*.yaml pathspec, a pattern (`name:`) known to match. Supersedes CONTROL-prep-grep-c-emits-colon-when-present, whose ':' expect a `fatal:` line satisfies. `ame:` cannot appear in any git error path. INVARIANT (b), SECOND CLAUSE: when a true negative implies NO OUTPUT, a same-argv positive control is a logical impossibility -- the same command can never print anything when the claim holds. The control must therefore run the same command SHAPE against the same substrate with a pattern KNOWN to match, and must assert a literal that the command's ERROR paths cannot produce. A bare ':' fails this: `fatal: cannot change to '<path>': No such file or directory` contains one, so a ':'-keyed control PASSES against a repo that does not exist."}
