// ---------------------------------------------------------------- ledger: invariant (b) hardening (CROSS-AUDIT)
// 🧪 harness's three `git grep -c` negative probes cannot take a same-argv positive control: a TRUE
// negative emits ZERO bytes, so the same command can never print anything. Their substitute controls
// (same repo, a pattern that IS present) are the right shape but chose a NON-DISCRIMINATING literal —
// `:` — which git's own `fatal: cannot change to '<path>': No such file` also satisfies. Proven: a
// control claim with expect=":" PASSES against /nonexistent-repo. The pair is safe today only because
// the probe shares that weak literal and inverts on it. These two controls assert a real `path:count`
// token, which no `fatal:` line can contain. Additive; harness's originals are untouched.
{"id": "no-ansible-uppercase-in-zsh-dotfiles-tracked", "kind": "cli-help", "must_fail": true, "file": "specs/macos-ci/09-dotfiles-under-test.md", "argv": ["git", "-C", "/Users/bossjones/dev/bossjones/zsh-dotfiles", "grep", "-h", "-o", "-i", "ansible"], "expect": "NSIBLE", "claim": "G9 casing completeness: `-o` preserves the matched text's case, so no-ansible-in-zsh-dotfiles-tracked's lowercase `nsible` cannot catch an all-caps `ANSIBLE`. This probe closes that hole. Same argv, same positive control (CONTROL-git-grep-o-i-emits-matched-text). Together the two probes cover ansible / Ansible / ANSIBLE.", "control": "CONTROL-git-grep-o-i-emits-matched-text", "polarity": "negative"}
