// --------------------------------------- ledger: GAP3/OQ-35 — the verifier, verified BY the verifier
// Every claim below EXECUTES tools/verify_claims.py against a checked-in fixture ledger and asserts
// on its real output. Each negative probe carries its positive control on the SAME argv.
{"id": "verifier-missing-file-emits-unreachable", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/12-tooling-and-agent-loop.md", "argv": ["uv", "run", "tools/verify_claims.py", "tests/fixtures/verifier/missing-file.jsonl"], "expect": "UNREACHABLE: missing file:", "claim": "EXECUTED, not grepped. Running verify_claims.py against a fixture ledger whose target file is absent emits `UNREACHABLE: missing file:`. Supersedes verify-claims-missing-file-is-unreachable, which was `file-contains` over the tool's own SOURCE: move that literal into a comment and delete the `except FileNotFoundError` handler and it stayed green (GAP3 / OQ-35). POSITIVE CONTROL for verifier-missing-file-is-not-inverted-into-a-pass on the same argv."}
{"id": "verifier-missing-file-is-not-inverted-into-a-pass", "kind": "cli-help", "must_fail": true, "control": "verifier-missing-file-emits-unreachable", "file": "specs/macos-ci/12-tooling-and-agent-loop.md", "argv": ["uv", "run", "tools/verify_claims.py", "tests/fixtures/verifier/missing-file.jsonl"], "expect": "[PASS]", "claim": "the `UNREACHABLE:` prefix is NEVER inverted by must_fail: the fixture's must_fail probe over an absent target prints [FAIL], never [PASS]. This is the behaviour that stops a deleted target file from turning a control green. Alone it is unfalsifiable \u2014 no output satisfies it too \u2014 so it is paired with verifier-missing-file-emits-unreachable on the SAME argv.", "polarity": "negative"}
{"id": "verifier-mustfail-inverts-a-plain-failure", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/12-tooling-and-agent-loop.md", "argv": ["uv", "run", "tools/verify_claims.py", "tests/fixtures/verifier/mustfail-inversion.jsonl"], "expect": "1/1 claims verified", "claim": "EXECUTED: a must_fail file-line at an out-of-range line yields a PLAIN failure (`line 999 out of range`), which must_fail inverts into a pass. This is the exact mechanism CONTROL-12-line-607-does-not-exist rests on. It was previously asserted only by the lead's hand-testing, recorded as prose on the board \u2014 the evidence class of Defect A."}
{"id": "verifier-rejects-an-uncontrolled-negative", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/12-tooling-and-agent-loop.md", "argv": ["uv", "run", "tools/verify_claims.py", "tests/fixtures/verifier/uncontrolled-negative.jsonl"], "expect": "STRUCTURAL REJECTION \u2014 negative evidence without a positive control", "claim": "EXECUTED: an `absent` record with no `control` is rejected structurally, before any evidence runs. Asserts the real message literal on the tool's real stderr. POSITIVE CONTROL for verifier-uncontrolled-negative-never-reaches-evaluation on the same argv."}
{"id": "verifier-uncontrolled-negative-never-reaches-evaluation", "kind": "cli-help", "must_fail": true, "control": "verifier-rejects-an-uncontrolled-negative", "file": "specs/macos-ci/12-tooling-and-agent-loop.md", "argv": ["uv", "run", "tools/verify_claims.py", "tests/fixtures/verifier/uncontrolled-negative.jsonl"], "expect": "claims verified", "claim": "the structural rejection happens BEFORE evaluation: the tool never prints `claims verified` for a ledger carrying an uncontrolled negative. Proves the check is a gate, not a warning. Paired with verifier-rejects-an-uncontrolled-negative on the SAME argv, which asserts the rejection message IS printed \u2014 without it, `no claims verified` would be satisfied by no output at all.", "polarity": "negative"}
{"id": "verifier-accepts-a-wellformed-pair", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/12-tooling-and-agent-loop.md", "argv": ["uv", "run", "tools/verify_claims.py", "tests/fixtures/verifier/wellformed-pair.jsonl"], "expect": "2/2 claims verified", "claim": "EXECUTED: a negative carrying its positive control over the same target is accepted and evaluated. The complement of verifier-rejects-an-uncontrolled-negative: the gate rejects the uncontrolled shape and admits the controlled one, so the rejection is discriminating rather than a blanket refusal."}
{"id": "CONTROL-verifier-oracle-fixture-executes", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/12-tooling-and-agent-loop.md", "argv": ["uv", "run", "tools/verify_claims.py", "tests/fixtures/verifier/oracle-exempt.jsonl"], "expect": "CONTROL-oracle-with-no-partner", "claim": "POSITIVE CONTROL for verifier-exempts-oracle-control-from-structural-check, same argv: the oracle fixture really is executed and its record really is reached. Deliberately asserts the claim id rather than `1/1 claims verified`, so a network outage (which would make the inner doc-index UNREACHABLE) cannot make this control silently vacuous."}
{"id": "verifier-exempts-oracle-control-from-structural-check", "kind": "cli-help", "must_fail": true, "control": "CONTROL-verifier-oracle-fixture-executes", "file": "specs/macos-ci/12-tooling-and-agent-loop.md", "argv": ["uv", "run", "tools/verify_claims.py", "tests/fixtures/verifier/oracle-exempt.jsonl"], "expect": "STRUCTURAL REJECTION", "claim": "a `CONTROL-*` record of a doc kind, must_fail, with no `control` field, is EXEMPT: it IS the oracle guard and has no partner by construction (GB5). The tool does not reject it. Paired with CONTROL-verifier-oracle-fixture-executes on the SAME argv.", "polarity": "negative"}
{"id": "CONTROL-terraform-registry-serves-a-known-provider", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/10-tart-vs-utm-adr.md", "argv": ["curl", "-sS", "-o", "/dev/null", "-w", "%{http_code}", "https://registry.terraform.io/v1/providers/hashicorp/aws"], "expect": "200", "claim": "POSITIVE CONTROL for no-terraform-provider-at-cirruslabs-tart and no-terraform-provider-at-cirruslabs-orchard (GAP1 / OQ-33). Those probes assert HTTP 404 from `registry.terraform.io/v1/providers/...`. A 404 is a NEGATIVE existence claim wearing positive clothes: `must_fail` is unset, so needs_control() never fires \u2014 it keys on the FLAG, not on what `expect` MEANS. If the registry ever moves `/v1/providers/`, BOTH probes keep printing 404 and keep passing, and the ledger would then 'prove' no Terraform provider exists when all it proves is that an endpoint moved. G1 is the first settled fact in CLAUDE.md. This control asserts a provider that certainly DOES exist still returns 200 from the same endpoint shape, so a 404 means absent-from-registry rather than registry-moved."}

