{"id": "g4-enforcement-press-release-returns-200", "kind": "http-status", "file": "specs/macos-ci/04-tart-licensing-risk.md", "url": "https://tart.run/blog/2025/10/27/press-release-cirrus-labs-successfully-enforces-its-fair-source-license/", "expect": "200", "claim": "the 2025-10-27 enforcement press release \u2014 the SOLE source for G4's 'enforcement is not theoretical', the highest-risk human-sign-off item in this repo \u2014 returns HTTP 200 despite being absent from tart's search index, which contains zero /blog/YYYY/MM/DD/ posts. A second G19, found this run. An agent applying 'absence from the index proves fabrication' outside the index's domain would retract the licensing evidence with total confidence. (OQ-26)"}
{"id": "packer-shell-uploads-the-varfile-into-the-guest", "kind": "http-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/13-build-secrets.md", "url": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/hashicorp/packer/v1.15.4/provisioner/shell/provisioner.go", "expect": "comm.Upload(remoteVFName", "claim": "packer v1.15.4's shell provisioner UPLOADS the env-var file into the guest (`comm.Upload(remoteVFName, ...)`, provisioner.go:273). This is why 13 mandates `use_env_var_file = false`: with `true`, the secret is written to the guest filesystem. Pinned at tag v1.15.4, never `main`. A substring grep of HashiCorp's rendered HTML is unsound \u2014 they split sentences across <code>/<span> \u2014 and there is no HashiCorp search-JSON oracle, so the pinned source is the only sound evidence. (OQ-13)"}
{"id": "packer-shell-cleans-the-varfile-with-an-unlink", "kind": "http-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/13-build-secrets.md", "url": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/hashicorp/packer/v1.15.4/provisioner/shell/provisioner.go", "expect": "\"rm -f %s\", path", "claim": "packer v1.15.4 removes the uploaded file with `rm -f` (provisioner.go:401) \u2014 an UNLINK, not a shred. It drops the directory entry; it does not zero the blocks. That is G15's whole point: a secret written into the guest survives in ~/.tart/vms/<name>/'s disk image and `strings` still finds it. Together with packer-shell-uploads-the-varfile-into-the-guest, this is the executable proof behind 13's central rule: never write the secret to the guest at all. (OQ-13)"}

